crops.Notes: Hortonova — optional. We find Hortonova to interfere with harvesting pansies and violas, so we no longer use it as support in this crop. However, depending on your preference, it can be useful for supporting taller varieties.   Brush Strokes: Earliest variety in our trials to have long enough stems to harvest. Nature Series: Almost as early as Brush Strokes; tall productive plants with beautiful color range. Frizzle Sizzle Series: later than Brush Strokes and slightly shorter, with unique, deeply ruffled blooms.  Sorbet Formula Mix: Best choice for edible flower production. This variety had the most consistent bloom production through the winter and early spring.   Stems stretch as the days lengthen, yielding harvestable (10–20") stems suitable for mixing into spring bouquets. Long harvest window. crops.Identifier: Radicchio (110 Day) - Forced Head 1X | Field TP Su
crops.Notes: Sew in trays around summer solstice (June 21st) through the first third of July says Osborne. Many varieties are differentiated by the DTM. Hard to grow, but doesn't sound like rocket science. Longer varieties are more cold hardy. 30 minutes in. https://www.notillgrowers.com/blog/2019/12/23/the-no-till-market-garden-podcast-with-evan-chendar-the-culinary-gardener. Hard to get dense heads which are necessary to get good texture, blanched color. Shorter varieties are easier to get a hit on. Nights in the 40s to head up for large varieties. Need gradual weather. Outer leaves self blanch when you force it. Forcing always develops a dense head. Even early varieties are cold hardy to 15 deg with AG-19 over short stints. Easy to force in water. Dig plants. trim slightly. Pack in crates insides a tub with a few inches of water + a heater under a lower tunnel raised on pallets. Force for three weeks. Change water twice a week. All nonf-roced are 6/lb. Forced are 20/lb. Target head is 0.5 lb up to 2lb. Sounds like early varieties are grown on 10 inch spacing. Why do the heads big? It seems riskier to do them larger and you can't fit as many to the bed. Seems better to do smaller tighter. Young Plants hardy to 5 deg. Mature hardy to 23 deg. Late-maturing varieties store longer than short-season varieties. https://www.osborneseed.com/catalog/cp_/catalog/vegetables/chicory/radicchio. Remay below 25. Possible to Spring force radicchio (would be less sweet but easier to heat)? https://uprisingorganics.com/pages/radicchiology https://extension.colostate.edu/docs/pubs/garden/07617.pdf. Assumune 2 lbs per plant. Typically plant less than three weeks before first frost. Much of the U.S. can plant in late march if fleeced. Midseason get planted in late april. Main crop get planted in mid apr - mid may. Earlier go late march - June. Midseason go late apr - late jul. Main crop go mid apr - mid may through aug. Heading varieties (Chioggia, Verona, Treviso precoce, Lusia, Rosa) are better sown towards the earlier part of this window. Looser or more cold tolerant varieties (Gorizia/Isontina, Castelfranco, Treviso Tardivo, Catalogna) or the earliest slotted varieties of the heading types, have more flexibility and can be successfully sown later in the window. Grumolo (a late winter/early spring harvested variety) can be sown into August.
